segments.text: Now I'm asking that you say something so this will record.
Let's pick you up over there.
Okay.
What do you want to talk about?
I wish we could talk about what a nice week it's been.
Well, I want an idea.
Now let's see if it's doing any better in between us.
Let's see.
Give your name, rate, horsepower, age, and everything else.
I'm Joan Rowe.
My horsepower is about zero right now.
I'm still going to be 59.
Today is February 27, and we're starting late in the morning at 6139 Berwyn in Dallas.
And I have the pleasure of talking to Bob Latimer, class of 44, who was president of the association in 1972.
Bob, why did you go to A&M in the first place?
Well, I was graduating from high school in Fort Worth in 1940.
Having grown up through the 30s,
Everyone knew that World War II was coming.
We didn't know what it would be called.
We didn't know how it would start or anything else.
But we knew it was impending.
That was one force of thought.
Another was that everyone, at least it was very clear to me,
having gone to grade school at Bayard, Texas, and high school in Fort Worth, that the only people that were going to get anywhere in this world had to have a college education.
Now, my family didn't have any money, and I set out to find scholarships wherever I could.
As it turned out, as my search had gone past, well,
Had to settle for TCU in Fort Worth and then in track at Arlington, neither of which I cared for.
And I tried for the military academies.
So I was really searching and A&M seemed beyond my reach until my uncle, class of 02, informed me of the newly
created opportunity award scholarship.
And the requirements for those as set out were the student had to have good grades and to have his note for $150 a year be endorsed by an A&M club.
When I understood that,
I felt like I had the grades to do it.
My uncle, though he had been long prominent in the association of former students, was not in a position to provide any tuition.
I didn't look for any from him.
But the way I went about it was to court the fourth A&M club
Every time they had a meeting, I went.
And they got to know me and know me well.
And so as the selection process evolved, well, I was granted one of the original Opportunity Award scholarships.
And how did you get to College Station when your first visit down there?
Well, one of my first visits,
was at the end of school in 1940, at the end of A&M.
My good friend Bob Halton, Bobby Halton, he was part of the Halton Jewish family in Fort Worth.
His mother and father took him and they took me down to pick up his brother who was
G.W.
Holden, who was the class of 42.
And that's the first time I saw her.
Basically, I only saw the then-new dorms as they finished their first year.
And we loaded up the car and went back to Fort Worth.
Then that fall, when you go as a student, how did you get down there?
Well, I was part of a
a rather active group in Fort Worth Basketball and Arlington Heights High School.
There was a big network of high school fraternities and sororities and they had frequent dances.
And the time for me to go A&M was a week ahead of time due to the fact that, I don't think I mentioned earlier,
The scholarship not only included getting a note endorsed by the Fort Worth A&M Club, but also would provide, while I was at school, a job that paid $150.
Well, my job was to be a janitor.
And that year, someone had the idea that it would be a good idea to train all the student janitors in janitoring.
which included mastering the mysteries of dormitory plumbing.
Well, they called for all of us would-be janitors to be there a week early.
And so the time for me to go, I went to a dance at the Fort Worth Casino and had a friend
get me into downtown Fort Worth in time for the 11 o'clock Owl, Missouri Pacific train.
And I rode that through the night and got thrown off the train at 5.30 in the morning at the College Station Station.
And not even having been in that spot before, all I could do was
after my footlocker on my back, and go up to the YMCA.
And I got up on the main floor, found one of those old porcelain couches, and lay down and finished the night until other people arrived.
All right.
Describe A&M physically in 1940 when you arrived.

Well, it was, of course it was, this was September the 11th I believe was the date, but it had been a hot summer and there wasn't much evidence of any moisture in the soil, so it was dusty everywhere.
The walk from
The railroad station to Hawaii was not arduous.
It just took a while.
Law and Ferrier Halls were there.
The Beagle Stand was out at the intersection of the walks.
And it was those buildings, the buildings there at the time were, of course,
I didn't know it was sold.
So I waited until people came awake and went over and reported to where they told us to.
And then I set about trying to adjust to the pattern.
All right.
Was the new core dorm area finished then?
It had been finished.
Where did you live your freshman year?

Well that first week I was in Leggett because that's close to where they had their school and when I was assigned a unit that was my my friend Haltman and I had applied to be roommates and that was granted and we were assigned to be and
H battery coast artillery which was assigned the top two floors of Mitchell Hall.
Now how did you happen to get that unit coast artillery?
Well I fight for coast artillery.
I've been an aviation dog all my high school life and I desperately wanted to get into flying and they said that
Part of the coach artillery's job was anti-aircraft, so I figured that was as close as you could get, and that set up fair.
Did you have the impression that people normally got the branch they requested, or was that unusual?
In general, they got what they asked for.
There was such a great, I guess you'd say, a great number that didn't have any idea what it was about.
And they obviously weren't trying to leave it to us.
Oh, yes, yes.
That first week was a rather interesting one.
Wendell Horsley was a great guy and later famous as a placement office man.
I was attracted to him.
He would always give me a friendly smile or a wink.
I adjusted to the rigors of no sheets or anything else in the old double deck bunks there in Leggett and got to the end of the week without
The thing that was notable about that is I got a little bit of insight into the school before the upperclassmen came in.
Now, were most of the trainees in this janitorial program, were most of those freshmen?
No, I think I was unusual.
Oh, okay.
I say I got used to it.
I bought some sheets, so I had sheets and kind of took care of my own business.
The thing that, well, the action began to happen on the following weekend, and the janitor's school was finished, and by then I...
more awareness, but certainly not any more knowledge of the dormitory plumbing than I had before.
Fortunately, my assignment in the janitorial job was the book stacks in the back of the library.
In Cushing?
In Cushing.
Oh.
And there's a number of stories that go with that.
But as far as
getting started, it was all a mystery.
And how Paulton and I were assigned room 77 in Mitchell Hall, we don't know.
But we went over there to, well, on Saturday when he came and the rest of them came,
we began to filter in and find our places.
Well, the sophomores and the juniors and seniors were coming around and beginning to look at places and see what was there and see where they were.
Now there, of course, the fifth year men, we had four of them, and the
seniors knew they got corner rooms and juniors got whatever was left in their favorite room.
We were on the, they called every floor a stoop.
And Alden and I were on the fourth stoop.
And Mitchell was in the shape of a figure eight.
So there was an inner courtyard.
We were on the fourth floor.
I guess at

courtyard was about 50 feet square and pavement on the bottom concrete so that any time a bottle or any other vulnerable piece of glassware landed it not only hit and splattered within there a heck of a racket but probably four stories four stories of walls up there so uh

But we got in and began to get, we very quickly were organized by the sophomores and indoctrinated that we had to speak to everybody and we had our names and then on was fish so and so and everyone else was mister and we had a fish strike it was called which was about a three-eighths of an inch white band
around our left cuff on our shirts, on the press uniforms while we just didn't have any service bar for a year.
Describe the issue of uniforms that the typical student had.
How many changes of what did you have?
Well, of course we were the
Every student, well I say every student, almost every student had to be in the Corps of Cadets.
We were enrolled, we went through over at the assembly hall which was then replaced by a chapel and then the assembly hall they had a
They arranged for it to provide clothing.
Assembly Hall and the Exchange Store, which was not far from, it was east of Leggett.
We were issued, as I recall,
with two khaki shirts, a tie, a wool blouse with blue lapels, and wool pants, and I don't know what they call it.
Socks?
Shoe.
Socks, shoes?
No shoes and no socks.
So you provided that.
Yes.
And did you have the little, what we would later call overseas caps yet?
What did you wear on your head?
Well, we had the garrison caps.
Oh, okay.
The round ones.
Okay.
And we also had overseas caps.
Okay.
And... On the... On the...
overseas cap, there was a distinctive colored braid to denote the branch that you were in.
In our case, we were artillery, so we had the right red band.
And did you, were you quickly reminded that you must speak in Aggie slang and lingo?
Well, you knew you, uh, about the
Second or third day, you began to get indoctrinated.
My thought process at the moment is getting a uniform on day, like on the Saturday and Sunday of Monday.
And the first night that everybody was there, which would have been the Sunday night, before, maybe Saturday before school started.
But all us freshmen were bunked up.
And every class, there was no mixing of classes in a single room.
Every room had either freshmen or sophomores or whatever the class was.
But there was no mix.
But about midnight, why, at the end of the shack, it occurred out in the hall.
And so we stuck our head out to see what was going on, and there was a fire, fire, fire.
And there were kids running up and down all over and hear the expression, come on president, come on president, come on president, it's on the fly.
Every poor face got to stand up and shake, and I don't believe a drop hit.
With all that had been heard and all of the apprehension and scared to death of what was going to happen next, I don't think that job hit them.
And that old floor, old Mitchell with the wooden floor placement, the floor was well worn.
So there really was a fire?
Oh, yeah.
There's some paper right there.
Oh, okay.
And this was probably not the first time that,
game had been played?
Well, it was for us.
No, but I mean, you think...
I expect those sophomores had some experience.
That's what I was wondering.
Now, did y'all use the same... was the slang then about what it is now as far as you know?
Y'all were fish and your roommate was your old lady?
Well, I...
I would submit...
that the 1990s version is basically more severe in a number of ways.
We didn't have anybody shouting at us, per se, like what has been carried over from the Marine Corps, per se.
and all that sort of thing.
We didn't have any of that.
The freshman had to walk in the streets.
If the freshman saw, well, they spoke to everyone, but if the freshman saw an upperclassman of his outfit, he spoke to Mr. So-and-so, and if Mr. So-and-so was talking to somebody else,
The freshman either knew the other person's name and called it, or else he went up and met him, introduced himself, and then went on his way.
That was, and to overlook introducing or speaking to an upperclassman's friend or acquaintance
was really a serious business.
Now, I'll back up a moment to say that I was on my guard about things because I had in some way acquired the book Fish Sergeant.
Have you seen Fish Sergeant?
Fish Sergeant was a little book about
It's been reprinted.
And Fish Sargent was a story of a kid named Fish Hooks.
And it went through all of the general repeated type
So I was on my guard and I didn't jump at everything and I wasn't quite, with all due respect to my buddies, I wasn't quite the sucker as a lot of them were.
Alright, so this book was kind of a, for you, a kind of a
A guide.
A guide.
A guide, but you know, I had read that thing through and through before I went down there because I was so apprehensive about all of the things in life at all that put me in depression.
Tell me about, where did y'all eat, and tell me about the chow hall routine.
Well, let me get over one more.
Oh, I'm sorry.
Let's say everybody was there on Sunday night.
I think it was the 18th, I'm not sure.
Everybody was there on Sunday night.
But we've been through the week during which, beginning the first night, everybody was there.
All the freshmen were gathered into a single room, and as many sophomores as we could crowd in.
The freshmen were all sitting on the floor.
And the sophomore proceeded to lecture on what it took to, quote, get the fish on the line, as dictated by the juniors and seniors.
Now, other than running,
details which are airing for our upperclassmen, let's say the juniors and seniors, the freshmen jumped to the sophomores primarily.
The sophomores were responsible for the behavior of the freshmen.
Sure.
And if the freshmen got lagged or didn't perform well or maybe just because the upperclassmen didn't like it anyway, why the freshmen would take it out.
seniors take it out on the junior, and the junior take it out on the sophomore.
Well, number one in this whole story is that we didn't, we were not touched by a board until after Thanksgiving.
The, but a bleed meeting would consist of all the instructions of walking in the street, speaking, meeting,
Yes, sir.
There were no, no exaggerated.
Yes, sir.
Or all that sort of none of that stuff.
There was no shoe polishing.
There's no brass box for the class.
Every cadet did his own.
The later years, all of my things thought that the notion of shining shoes and
and so on and just into all of it.
Were there any things that you now look back on that you think of were inappropriate hazing in your days?
No, not really.
There have been some rough times at A&M.
I mean by that, oh, I think it was in the 30s.
seven or eight while I was there.
There was a big furor over the possibility the railroad might move the station in the blind.
The field artillery got out there with their 75 guns and lined them up on the tracks and informed the railroad they were going to have a station there.
No, but I mentioned that but also there had been a couple of pretty rough incidents and so the word was out early on that nobody would get the board until after Thanksgiving.
Thanksgiving of course was the mid-semester break
The grades were out and then you'd see how many were going to be there.
The most telling thing of all of that was that Dr. Brayden, who was a venerable and long-time theater and chemistry department.
B-R-A-Y-H-R Brayden.
We went to his first chemistry lecture.
I was in engineering, an old freshman taking engineering at an identical curriculum.
I never shall forget the first day I sat in that chemistry lecture room.
There were about 330 boys in there.
And the first thing he said was, look at the guy in front of you and the one behind you.
One on your right and one on your left.
He said there'd be one of you graduates.
I guess among everybody that was the most telling statement that they'd encountered.
Did that add to your determination?
Oh yeah.
But I had to be under my bonnet because I didn't have enough money to go anywhere.
My father had money when I was younger, but it was not available when I came around.
But I was determined to do the best I could at A&M to get the best job opportunity when I got out.
And that's all I needed.
All right, let's go back to the chow hall now.
Tell me about meals and where they were and what the routine was.
Meals were at, I think I'm right, 7 a.m., noon, and 5.45 p.m.
There would be a whistle in the dawn five minutes ahead of time to
And we were in Mitchell Hall, which is now where the infirmary is.
But that was on the, we were the nearest, and across the military walk was the, we were the nearest dorms to Sbisa.
And when everybody was in position,
All the way down military wall.
